In 1858 it was referred to as the "white-headed goose" (Spencer Baird, "Birds", edited by Cassina and Lawrence) while the Snow Goose referred to Anser/Chen hyperboreus, which was specifically what is now the white morph of Anser caerulescens. In Cuban Spanish in [year] it was called the "Guanana prieta", which as far as I can tell means "brown goose" and is shared with Anser gambelii (Contribucion á la ornitologia cubana, Gundlach, 1876). Agersborg (Auk, 1885) calls the snow goose Chen hyperboreus, whereas Chen caerulescens is the blue-winged goose. He notes that snow geese feet "often freeze in winter unless they are kept [warm]". SO. Because the name "snow goose" originally applied to Chen hyperboreus, and hyperboreus translates to "extreme far north", I am going to put this as geographic description.

Some ascribe it to the Dutch word dodoor for "sluggard", but it is more probably related to Dodaars, which means either "fat-arse" or "knot-arse", referring to the knot of feathers on the hind end.[29] The first record of the word Dodaars is in Captain Willem Van West-Zanen's journal in 1602.[30] The English writer Sir Thomas Herbert was the first to use the word dodo in print in his 1634 travelogue claiming it was referred to as such by the Portuguese, who had visited Mauritius in 1507.[28]  Another Englishman, Emmanuel Altham, had used the word in a 1628 letter in which he also claimed its origin was Portuguese. The name "dodar" was introduced into English at the same time as dodo, but was only used until the 18th century.[31] As far as is known, the Portuguese never mentioned the bird. Nevertheless, some sources still state that the word dodo derives from the Portuguese word doudo (currently doido), meaning "fool" or "crazy". It has also been suggested that dodo was an onomatopoeic approximation of the bird's call, a two-note pigeon-like sound resembling "doo-doo".[32]
COMMENT_E: Borrowed from Portuguese doudo, obsolete form of doido (“fool, simpleton, silly, stupid”). First attested in the 17th century.
